London-listed stocks remained steady on Monday, taking a breather after a recent rally as investors assessed ongoing market conditions. Notably, HSBC shares fell by 1% following the bank's disclosure that its third-quarter results will reflect a $1.1 billion provision linked to a partial court appeal loss concerning Bernard Madoff's infamous Ponzi scheme.
Both the FTSE 100 and FTSE 250 showed modest gains of 0.1% each, bolstered by hopes of impending interest rate cuts by the Bank of England, spurred by moderating inflationary pressures. Last week, the FTSE 100 reached record heights, while the FTSE 250 climbed to levels not seen in nearly four years, signaling investor confidence.
Globally, positive sentiment hints at a potential U.S.-China trade agreement, causing a dip in safe-haven assets like gold. Domestically, investors witnessed a notable surge in mid-cap Goodwin's shares after an optimistic profit forecast. However, Greencore's proposed merger faced scrutiny from the UK's competition authority, highlighting challenges within the marketplace.
(With inputs from agencies.)
